,"1135–1205":"1135–1205","1094–1147":"1094–1147","1099–Female":"1099–Deceased","1205":"1205","1147":"1147","1135":"1135","about 1125":"about 1125","1099":"1099","1120":"1120","1174":"1174","about 1135":"about 1135","1094":"1094","about 1174":"about 1174","about 1120":"about 1120","1119":"1119","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Skipwith, Yorkshire, England":"Skipwith, Yorkshire, England","England":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Langton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from one or more of the many places called with Old English <i>lang</i> ‘long’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, such as Langton Hall in Kirkby in Ashfield (Nottinghamshire), Langton Lodge in Hendon (Middlesex), Langton (Yorkshire), East and West Langton (Leicestershire), Langton by Horncastle, Langton by Spilsby, and Langton by Wragby (all in Lincolnshire), and Lanton (Northumb). Compare   Lankton  ,   Lanton  , and   Longton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lanton","meanings":["English: variant of   Langton  ."]},{"name":"Lankton","meanings":["English: variant of   Langton  .","History: Thomas Lankton, born <i>c.</i> 1714 in Hartford County, CT, died 1783 in Litchfield County, CT, was a son of Joseph Langton."]},{"name":"Longton","meanings":["habitational name from Longton in Lancashire. The placename derives from Old English <i>lang</i> ‘long’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’.","variant of   Langton  .","English:"]}]},{"name":"Beatrix","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Late Latin personal name, which was borne by a saint martyred in Rome, together with Saints Faustinus and Simplicius, in the early 4th century. The original form of the name was probably <i>Viatrix</i>, a feminine version of <i>Viator</i> ‘voyager (through life)’, which was a favourite name among early Christians. This was then altered by association with Latin <i>Beatus</i> ‘blessed’ (<i>Via-</i> and <i>Bea-</i> sometimes being pronounced the same in Late Latin).  See also  Beatrice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Beatrix de Langton was born about 1120, in Skipwith, Yorkshire, England, her father, Sir Pagant de Langton, was 28 and her mother, Mrs Pagan de Langtun, was 22. She had at least 1 son with Patrick de Stuteville de Schypwith. She died in 1174, in Lincolnshire, England, at the age of 55."},"et":{"about 1120–1174":"umbes 1120–1174","1120–1174":"1120–1174","1135–1205":"1135–1205","1094–1147":"1094–1147","1099–Female":"1099–Surnud","1205":"1205","1147":"1147","1135":"1135","about 1125":"umbes 1125","1099":"1099","1120":"1120","1174":"1174","about 1135":"umbes 1135","1094":"1094","about 1174":"umbes 1174","about 1120":"umbes 1120","1119":"1119","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Skipwith, Yorkshire, England":"Skipwith, Yorkshire, England","England":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1120–1174":"noin 1120–1174","1120–1174":"1120–1174","1135–1205":"1135–1205","1094–1147":"1094–1147","1099–Female":"1099–Kuollut","1205":"1205","1147":"1147","1135":"1135","about 1125":"noin 1125","1099